==English==

===Etymology===
The phrase was created in World War II with the usage meaning that a product met the highest standards of quality and would not be accepted by Uncle Sam if it did not. <ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/terry-newell/good-enough-for-governmen_b_792162.html]</ref>
The phrase was used as early as 1906 in Canada with the usage being neither disparaging nor better than non-government work.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=MxEyAQAAMAAJ&pg=PR245&dq=%22good+enough+for+government+work%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CCYQ6AEwAGoVChMIoZ_ph8GuyAIVyxg-Ch0gswbf#v=onepage&q=%22good%20enough%20for%20government%20work%22&f=false]</ref>. It was used disparagingly as early as 1960<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=pmt68RIT0t4C&q=%22good+enough+for+government+work%22&dq=%22good+enough+for+government+work%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CCYQ6AEwAGoVChMIysCpiMOuyAIVi5UeCh1TMw6B]</ref>.

